commentBody:
@logical 

This is now the third attempt I've made to reply to this comment.  I think the problem is the name of a religion I mentioned each time.  So I'll forgo naming that religion, and say that your glib comment might offend quite a few people, and this article might explain why:

<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hijrah" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hijrah</a>

@Steve L 

(Referees blow whistles.)

@Steve L for being too clever for our emus.  15 yards and loss of down.

@logical 

You should be careful.  It may sound like pure gibberish to you, but you run the risk of offending a whole lot of Muslims.  

(Second attempt.)

@Dave S 

I was going to guess Dune (seems to lean a bit Arabic), but then I discovered there is actually an old Sci-Fi novel with that title:



<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hegira_(novel" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hegira_(novel</a>)

@Vaer 

I am a gardener. I don’t recall using or hearing that word order. (Not that it’s not a valid term.). Aside from “bed of roses”, I might allow “rose garden”, which is what we use to refer to our area of five huge rose bushes that we have in one corner of our large backyard. 

I think “flower bed” is far more in-the-language.

@CCed 
Even 5 years in, Fridays can be pretty challenging. This puzzle was the perfect level of crunchy and fun for me. I wish I hadn’t stuck with Oct-AVE for as long as I did. And I must have skipped class when HEGIRA was taught 😊
Off to enjoy a ridiculously warm (and windy) day in the Windy City. Peace

@fionatimes 

I had never heard of hegira before, so that was a fun one to learn about (and now I have a Joni Mitchell album to check out).

Sending out a "Whats a good boy!" your kitty from across the interwebs.

@Bob T. 

I'm not much of a baseball fan, but I do like Fogerty's song. (I had an earworm of it, too.)

Thanks for the video. I recognized maybe half a dozen of the old MLB players. When I was a kid, I had a book that had short biographies of baseball stars from Ty Cobb to Mickey Mantle; I must've read it five times.

@Eric Hougland 

You're so welcome!
And I agree!

@Andrzej 

Re:  press

Multiple meanings for the word, but one is "to insist on" as in "The policeman pressed the suspect for the name of his accomplice."

@Andrzej I do love a good SPIT TAKE, and I'm sure you've seen them in movies or on SNL. Under certain circumstances it's also fun to wait until someone is taking a sip and then say something you know will make them laugh. ;)

I found some compilations I didn't really like; this segment on James Cordon isn't bad, but I think you don't like short videos. this is about 3 minutes.

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IRZC58WbMaQ" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IRZC58WbMaQ</a>

@Steve L 

Like ONCELET?  Since it's ONCELER, actually.  

I think you are lecturing people for crimes they haven't committed.  As with "RE-ENTRIES"--where most of us were primed to think "Football" after the  QB clue-- people expressed bafflement, but I didn't see anyone blaming editors or the constructor forr their confusion.

@Tim 

Right? I mean, I did not even notice this while solving, but I just can't see how the clue with -ing works with SPEED RUN as either a verb or a noun. 

Would "Running 42k" solve to "marathon"? Or "Building a house" to "construction"? I don't have enough of a linguistic intuition in English to answer these questions. Any help?

@Tim I see your point, but this sort of misdirect happens later in the week. Example sentences:

What are you doing today? I'm planning a speed run on the new game. OR My goal is finishing the new game as fast as possible. 

Both are objects. Not 100% parallel, need some small words, but it works. I hope my sentences are something a person would actually say, I am not all a gamer. For this type of clue, I think, can I possibly shove the two in the same sort of sentence? If so, it's on.

@Tim The way I resolved this, thanks to Gregg above, is that
Completing a game as fast as possible = a speedrun

It was a nice fake out for a Friday.

@Mitzi Thanks. I kind of see it.

But I mainly see it as Phil above, who I notice is also from the UK. And Pete's reply to Phil references British cryptic crosswords, which are generally stricter on definitions (by necessity).

As most UK crossworders here probably grew up on cryptic crosswords, that could be why there's a difference of opinion! That doesn't mean we're right, of course, maybe we need to chill out a bit ;-)

@joel88s No doubt - the question though is whether the "rules" say that a gerund has to be clued with another gerund (completing = speedrunning), or whether noun = noun is sufficient.

And I now know that apparently the latter is the case!

Though clearly plural noun = plural noun IS a rule, so it's not obvious where the line is (it's not as simple as noun = noun).

@Nancy J. 

Oh, so that was not about football? I thought it was an American football thing so I just ignored it :D.

Does it have something to do with reentering the atmopshere by a space shuttle before touchdown? That's the only thing I can come up with... I see now the column says it's about airplanes, but they don't leave the atmosphere, so what are they reentering, exactly? I like the space shuttle theory better. Please tell me if you think I'm wrong.

@Andrzej 

Yes, it's related to spacecraft reentering the atmosphere.  Great misdirect!

Deb made a rare mistake in her column.

@Mean Old Lady 

Strangely, I find Worlde very easy: my success rate is over 98%, and I get it in 3 or 4 tries, on most days.

Over the years I have learned what letters are most common, which helps. I am not a bot though, so I start with ADIEU rather than CRANE :D

@Steve L 

I think it's idiosyncratic, to some extent. I tried different words to open, but I always find myself coming back to ADIEU. Maybe my being Polish influences this choice? I wouldn't know why and how, but who knows.

STERN looks like it would be a good opening, indeed. SLANT too. Maybe I'll try them 🙂

@joel88s 

"Schtick" has become a commonly used word in English. It's in any number of dictionaries, including ME. It's not at all obscure. Now, ONCELER...to me, at least, that one was obscure.

"Bench press?" appeared to be about weightlifting, but that was a misdirect.

@joel88s 
I'm not sure what a "tonal connection" would even be in these situations. Was the word "shtick" not serious enough to convey a knight's HONOR? "Shtick" literally just means "thing a person is known for." And knights are known for their HONOR.

As for "Bench press," doesn't the clue sort of match the answer? They're both athletic-themed, at least. Really not understanding the complaint. It sounds like you just don't like wordplay, in which case I would suggest getting a new hobby.

@Katie Sorry you're right 'tonal connection' is a bit amorphous, but I gave a few examples above (of many, many candidates) that do have it to my mind. But of course it's subjective so if you don't feel the difference then you don't.

Actually your analysis of "knight shtick" hits the mark pretty well: yes "shtick" means the thing you're known for, but it doesn't mean "just" that; it carries the connotation of a contrived comedic act - so like you say, not serious enough, in fact totally opposite to and discordant with the notion of a knight's honor. I think that is indeed what rubbed me the wrong way about it.

And an "athletic" connection between 'bench press' and 'put me it, coach' feels artificial and contrived to me; more meaningful is simply the pun on 'bench.' But to contrast with one of the 'better' examples I mentioned... reparsing 'ranch dressing' as 'what you might wear on a ranch' (a STETSON HAT) is natural and pleasing, whereas reparsing 'bench press' as... 'something-you-might-press-someone-to-do-while-sitting-on-the-bench'? - not so much to my ear.

@Andrew F 

ENDAT was one of a handful of entries on the right side that made me take double my normal Friday time today, in part because of a couple nearby entries that ate my lunch (ONCELER and SOO were both completely unknown to me, and opaque to the eye once filled in via crosses), but also due to the fuzziness of the match between “stop by” and “end at”.

That said: I’m pretty sure the intended manner of connection is your #2, and while those phrases aren’t *exactly* synonymous, I’d say they’re close enough for crosswording.

@Bob T. 

Oh wow, SOO has appeared in *lots* of puzzles: <a href="https://www.xwordinfo.com/Finder?w=SOO" target="_blank">https://www.xwordinfo.com/Finder?w=SOO</a>

…but with the “Great Lakes canal” meaning, it hasn’t been used since 2019. So I don’t feel horrible about my lack of recall. (Better believe it’s in the bank now, though)

@Helen Wright 
"mad as a box of frogs"

This is my new favorite saying.

@Helen Wright 
Thanks all 😀
I had no idea my ‘mad as a box of frogs’ phrase was unusual!  @Bruce, maybe I need to visit Georgia. I’ll leave it four years though.

@Peter, do we even call it a bench? I thought it was the subs box. I take no notice of the footie and in the absence of DH (Exeter City fan so ‘football’ is a loose term) I have no expert at hand.

@Teresa 

Note that 59A has an "e.g." in the clue without any abbreviation in the answer as well.  Commonly used abbreviations don't always signal one in the answer, and "Shak." is a commonly used abbreviation in attributions to quotations.

Check out the various answers that clues with U.S. in them that are not abbreviated, most recently Saturday with [Dollars : U.S. :: ___ : Nigeria], solving to NAIRAS and also [Great Plains aquifer that supplies over a quarter of U.S. irrigation water], solving to OGALLALA.  (Of course, some others do have abbreviations in the answer, but it's not a requirement.)

@Teresa oh oh oh! pick me! I know!

If you look at the newspaper version, you'll see that spelling his name in full would have added a line. It's all about the real estate. ;)

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/svc/crosswords/v2/puzzle/print/Mar1425.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/svc/crosswords/v2/puzzle/print/Mar1425.pdf</a>

@JD Gold 
"Okay, we'll start digging at 10, but we'll stop by noon."

Does that clear things up?

@Katie 

I think the issue is that "stop by" means to finish before the time (or possibly exactly at the time), whereas END AT means specifically at the time.

Since there is some overlap, I think the clue is fine, but others don't agree.

@Jeremy 

We will annex your country, and you will be happy about it.

Just kidding.

@Grant 

The books by this guy were completely unknown over here when I was a child. I have no idea if that has changed over the past few decades. Anyway, ONCELER looked like random letters to me today.

To be fair, Americans probably are equally clueless about Sierotka Marysia :D

@Tricia109 

You're so welcome!

"May life imitate art" - as is said, from your lips to God's ears...

@Byron 

My parents were off the hook for that one. It was a very safe neighborhood in a NY suburb, so the strain was on my older brothers who were tasked with accompanying me. 

The waddle was fun and wasn't too hard to imitate - I was a ballet student and my feet already jutted outward when I walked, so that was halfway there! :-)

@Steve 

I have a dog, and it held me up, too.

I'm sure that if I looked at the picture of today's Wordplay column, I would have got it right away!

@RobJ Thanks everyone!
I think it was a case of Google translate being a bit TOO helpful and assuming I meant Español when I'd typed Española.

"Poor little fella, he's put an extra a at the end. Let's not tell him and just translate what he must have meant"

@RobJ 

Española also means Spanish, but in the feminine form, such as "una mujer española" for "a Spanish woman".  But it never used in the feminine as the name of the language, as languages are always masculine nouns.

And although both the Galápagos Islands and the Greater Antilles in the Caribbean have an island with the same name, it's the one with Haiti and the Dominican Republic that is widely known, so I'm pretty sure they're referring to that one.

@Grant 

If I'm solving on my computer, I don't have to scroll to see it. My monitor is pretty large so it's just right there under the puzzle.

It's not a problem at all if I'm solving on my phone of course.

@D 

I thought the clues were so delightful! 

Can you share which ones didn't make sense to you?

@Shari Coatsi 
We had snow here in N. Cal too, big wet flakes melting before they even hit the ground.
We get it about once a year and it rarely stays on the ground past noon. Today, not at all.

@Cal Gal @Shari

Y'all are having snow in California and here in Minnesota it's 76° and lovely.

🤷‍♀️

@Darren 
I had a tough time today too, not with the same words you mentioned, but still it was just hard for me.
However, I’d probably never blame the puzzle because I couldn’t come up with all the answers…clearly my problem.
